\description{
Fetches an SDG indicator via \code{\link[=sdg_data]{sdg_data()}} and summarises how each
constituent \strong{series} is covered, by location and year. SDG
indicators are typically published as several series stratified
by sex, age, cause, vaccine, or similar — for example, indicator
\code{"3.b.1"} (vaccine coverage) is split into \code{SH_ACS_DTP3},
\code{SH_ACS_MCV2}, \code{SH_ACS_PCV3}, and \code{SH_ACS_HPV}. Each series can
have its own country / year coverage; \code{sdg_coverage()} makes
those differences visible before committing to an analysis.

A single SDG indicator (for example \code{"3.4.1"}, NCD mortality) is
typically published as several \strong{series} stratified by sex, age,
or cause. Different series may have different country and year
coverage. \code{sdg_coverage()} summarises year range and observation
count per \verb{(location, series)} combination, so you can see which
series exist for an indicator and how each one is covered before
committing to a downstream analysis.
}
\details{
This is a \emph{series-exploration} helper, not an availability
precheck. SDG data is generally complete enough that GHO-style
\code{\link[=gho_has_data]{gho_has_data()}} / \code{\link[=gho_count]{gho_count()}} analogues add little value, and
are intentionally not provided. The more useful pre-analysis
question for SDG is "which series exist, and how is each
covered?", which is what this function answers.

Unlike the GHO availability helpers, this function is a
series-exploration tool rather than a payload-saving precheck:
SDG data is generally complete enough that GHO-style
\code{has_data()} / \code{count()} helpers add little value, so they are
intentionally not provided. The SDG API also offers no
payload-reduction option (no \verb{$select} equivalent), so
\code{sdg_coverage()} calls \code{\link[=sdg_data]{sdg_data()}} internally and aggregates
the result client-side.
